## üî¥ CRITICAL Rules (Must Follow)

### 1. NO `any` Type - EVER
```typescript
// ‚ùå FORBIDDEN
const data: any = response;

// ‚úÖ REQUIRED
const data: ApiResponse<User> = response;
```

### 2. Tailwind CSS ONLY
```html
<!-- ‚ùå FORBIDDEN -->
<div style="color: red; padding: 10px;">

<!-- ‚úÖ REQUIRED -->
<div class="text-red-500 p-2.5">
```

### 3. Never Modify Shared Components
```typescript
// ‚ùå FORBIDDEN - Don't modify shared components
// src/app/shared/components/button.component.ts

// ‚úÖ REQUIRED - Create feature-specific component
// src/app/features/users/components/user-button.component.ts
```

### 4. Always Use OnPush Change Detection
```typescript
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
```

## üü° WARNING Rules (Should Follow)

- Use `trackBy` in all `*ngFor` loops
- Unsubscribe from observables in `ngOnDestroy`
- Write tests for all components (80%+ coverage)
- Use mobile-first responsive design
- Add JSDoc comments to public methods

## üìã Component Checklist

Before committing any component:
- [ ] No `any` types
- [ ] OnPush change detection
- [ ] Standalone component
- [ ] @Input/@Output properly typed
- [ ] Unsubscribe in ngOnDestroy
- [ ] trackBy in *ngFor loops
- [ ] Tailwind CSS only (no custom CSS)
- [ ] Responsive design (mobile-first)
- [ ] No console.log statements
- [ ] Tests written (80%+ coverage)
- [ ] JSDoc comments added

## üé® Styling Rules

- **ONLY** use Tailwind CSS utilities
- **NO** custom CSS files (except for component-specific styles when absolutely necessary)
- **NO** inline styles
- Use CSS variables for theme colors: `var(--accent-color)`, `var(--accent-gradient-from)`, etc.
- Mobile-first approach with responsive breakpoints: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`, `2xl:`

## üöÄ Performance Rules

- Use OnPush change detection strategy
- Unsubscribe from observables using `takeUntilDestroyed` or `DestroyRef`
- Use `trackBy` functions in `*ngFor` loops
- Lazy load routes and feature modules
- Use `async` pipe when possible
- No over-engineering - keep it simple

